This patch introduces two new operands for the qnum type. The first is bitlength(qnum), a unary prefix builtin that returns the number of qubits (bits) in a qnum register as a cnum. The second is amplitude indexing via qnum[x] and qnum['bstr'], which reads or writes the complex amplitude of a specific basis state within the qnum superposition. Index access by integer selects by state index in standard binary computational basis order (000=0, 001=1, 010=2, etc.). Index access by quoted binary string selects by the explicit bit pattern. Both forms return a cnum (complex). On write, the qnum is automatically renormalised after the amplitude is set. The write form z[3] = 4 or z['010'] = 4 sets the amplitude of that basis state to the given cnum value and then renormalises the full state vector. Attempting to access an index >= 2^(num_qubits) is an error. Attempting to set an amplitude with a string index whose length does not match the number of qubits in the register is an error. A string index that contains characters other than '0' and '1' is an error.
New Syntax
bitlength(q)   -- returns number of qubits in q as cnum
bitlength q    -- unary prefix form
q[3]           -- read amplitude at basis index 3, returns cnum
q['010']       -- read amplitude at basis state |010>, returns cnum
q[3] = v      -- set amplitude at basis index 3 to v, then renormalise
q['010'] = v  -- set amplitude at basis state |010> to v, then renormalise
Return Types
bitlength: always cnum.
qnum[x] (read): cnum (complex amplitude, imaginary part may be zero).
qnum[x] = v (write): cnum (the value assigned, before renormalisation).
Design Notes
The existing IndexExpr AST node is reused for qnum amplitude access. When the type checker identifies that the object of an IndexExpr is a qnum and the index is a single value (integer or string literal), it resolves the result type as cnum. The type checker also permits qnum index assignment (IRAssign with IRIndex target on a qnum). The string-index form with a quoted binary string is resolved at runtime, not at the string-literal level; the string is treated as a binary address. Renormalisation after write uses the existing QuantumState::normalise method. bitlength is a new keyword added as KW_BITLENGTH throughout the pipeline.
